			<tr><td colspan="2">
				<div class="postbody">
				Hopefully this will wrack a few brains!  Ok here's the situation:
<br />

<br />
I just bought a new 80 gig hard drive for my main personal computer at home (Yes i really have like 10 computers!).  It already has 2 drives in it but what I'm looking to do is dual boot linux and windows off their own hard drive.  Not a tough task.  What i have in my computer now is:
<br />

<br />
- a 30 gig with Windows and my windows apps  installed
<br />

<br />
- a 160 gig (already partitioned with NTFS from when it was in my main computer, and i have it almost filled to the brim with personal and business files I really don't want to lose).  This drive is split into 2 partitions ~80 gigs each.  I've had this drive for quite a while and when I partitioned it I used fdisk and had no problems doing so.  I've set up probably 178891289379812.4x10^9 drives.
<br />

<br />
- an 80 gig I plan on slapping on none other than a fresh install of Gentoo linux.  I loooove Gentoo!
<br />

<br />
So...here's the dilemma:
<br />

<br />
My WinXP install obviously detects my partitions on my 160 just fine.  Under both Windows explorer and the disk management tool It shows it as 2 healthy partitions on my drive.  No problem there.
<br />

<br />
When I loaded Gentoo (2.6 kernel I might add) I could not for the life of me  get it to find my 160 gig drive.  I tried and tried but could not get it mounted.  I thought I'd do a little further investigation.  I fired up cfdisk and checked the partitions of the 160.  It DOES detect the drive but it shows it as a 7 gig partition in EZ-Drive (WTF!) and the rest is unpartitioned.  Clearly this is not correct!  omg!
<br />

<br />
I tried with SuSE 9.1 (2.6!) and it still could not find this drive...
<br />

<br />
Here's when I decided to try Knoppix.  I loaded up off the Knoppix CD and sure enough it not only automatically detected my drive, but put a nice little friendly icon on the desktop for each partition.  I was pretty shocked at this point.  I checked fdisk in knoppix and it detects them as two partitions in NTFS (good) and I checked fstab and it has them mounted as NTFS drives, 80 gigs in size and everything.  I can even view and read the files inside the drives.  Knoppix is using the 2.4 kernel.  
<br />

<br />
I put in my windows xp disk and checked fdisk.  It shows the drive as having about 30 gigs partitioned in NTFS and the rest is damaged or unformatted.  WTFizzle!
<br />

<br />
I tried installing Windows 2000 pro AND XP pro on this 80 gig just for testing purposes.  They did NOT detect the drive correctly....only my current winxp install and knoppix.
<br />

<br />
So what I know is this (short summary for those who didn't want to read this crap):
<br />

<br />
- 160 gig drive, 2 partitions 80 gigs each.  Very important files!  Cannot lose them!
<br />

<br />
- Gentoo install using 2.6 kernel does not like this drive for whatever reason.  And what is EZ-Drive?
<br />

<br />
- SuSE 9.1 will also not detect this drive.  I cannot CANNOT get this drive mounted.  It gives me the incorrect file system blah blah error (I'm not at my computer now or i would give specifics... sorry)
<br />

<br />
- Knoppix 2.4 kernel DOES detect this drive automatically.  Nothing wrong here.  Happy me!
<br />

<br />
- Windows XP and 2k NEW INSTALL does NOT detect this drive properly.
<br />

<br />
- ONLY my current XP install and Knoppix detect this drive normally.
<br />

<br />
- When Partition Magic is used with this drive plugged in, I don't even get to the app as it tells me EZ Drive is corrupt on one of my disks!  What!?
<br />

<br />
I realize with Linux, writing to NTFS is kinda sketchy as of now, but this is just simple hdd detection.
<br />

<br />
What is wrong with this drive?  What am I doing wrong?  HOW do I mount this thing?  Any tips for getting this thing mounted in a 2.6 kernel linux?  I'm not a newbie but i think something is seriously wrong here... maybe even wrong with my drive..
<br />

<br />
Here is what I think is wrong:
<br />
- either the partitioning on my drive is completely jacked somehow.
<br />
- the drive is bad (or going bad.. NOOOO!!)
<br />
- something with linux 2.6 and my drive is causing it to not be detected.
<br />

<br />
My next step probably is to load up knoppix again and further investigate WHY it is detecting this drive and how.  Either way I think I'm going to start backing up this drive both to avoid possible failure and i might repartition it just so I know how it's set up.
<br />

<br />
If you got here, THANKS for reading <img src="images/smiles/badrazz.gif" alt="badrazz" border="0" />  Any help will be sooooooo appreciated!!!!!<br />
				<span class="gensmall"></span><br />
