			<tr><td colspan="2">
				<div class="postbody">
				Your BIOS is seeing it as a 33GB drive?
<br />

<br />
Check your drive's jumper settings.  You may have turned on the 32GB clip option many drives come with.  Also check your BIOS's seettings for the drive.  You may have LBA turned off.  You may also have a buggy BIOS or attached it to a controller that does not play well with the drive.
<br />

<br />
Which Gentoo version are you using and what kernel (2.6 is too broad) is it booting with.  Is it 2005.1?  I could do a lot more for ya if you would dump the dmesg into a post.  Gentoo install comes with an ssh server that you can start up and you can scp files to another machine in a network if you dont wanna bother with links.  I'm sure you know that:
<br />

<br />
#dmesg &gt; ~/postme.txt
<br />

<br />
Will let you save it and fetch it easily.
<br />

<br />
Alternately you could just putty in and dmesg to your terminal and copy and paste from there...
<br />

<br />
Troubleshooting hardware without the kernel's output is really tough.  There is a chance that the output from lspci may be useful too <img src="images/smiles/smile.gif" alt="smile" border="0" /><br />
				<span class="gensmall"></span><br />
				</div>
			</td></tr>
		</table>
		</td>
